ado. It is at once a deeply personal narrative and an homage to the lost relationship of the Czech, German, and Jewish peoples. In 2002, The Sound of the Sundial received the Czech Republic’s prestigious Magnesia Litera Award in the category of Best New Discovery, just a few years before its young author died. It is making its world premiere appearance in English here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCzech fictiony21st century. 0aMan-woman relationshipsvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aCzech.  aMagnesia Litera Award.  aTheresienstadt.  aZlín.  afiction.  anovel.1 aBajaja, Antonín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiranda Feingold, Rachel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShort, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311102355740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781951508081?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781951508081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781951508081/original  a978-3-11-102355-7  Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK